s><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-173-27-0047"><gtr:id>746F5817-1755-42C5-8F7C-7176BFE90864</gtr:id><gtr:title>Placement Fellowship in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0047</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The main aim of the research was to investigate the views of Muslim theologians and scholars. Focusing on politically moderate and theologically progressive Muslim leaders, the research was led by an interest in the interpretation of religion in the view of current social and political challenges.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />Engaging in fieldwork and using interviews to collect qualitative data, the research intended to provide a clearer understanding of the following key questions:
&lt;br />
&lt;br />
&lt;ul>
 &lt;li>What does it mean to read the Qur?an in the light of modernity?&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>What is Islamic law and how does it relate to todays issues?&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>Is the idea of corporal punishment an essential part of Islamic law?&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>What is an Islamic state and is there a need to work towards establishing such a state?&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>What is the meaning of Jihad?&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>Are women equal to men?&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>The principal output of the research was in form of a policy report with the title 'Muslim Theologians and Scholars: Moderate and Progressive Voices'. The report presents the aims of the research, gives a detailed description of methods used in the collection of data and, finally, provides a analysis of the interviews which directly feed into a set of policy recommendations.
